subSubSection.paragraph:
Male antenna (
Fig. 1
) short, nearly reaching the abdomen. First flagellomere slightly broader than following ones; f 1 1.5–1.8 times longer than f 2 and 2.1–2.7 times longer than pedicel. Flagellomeres decrease in length from the 1 st to the 4 th one and increase in length distally starting from the 5 th one. Verticils three to four times as long as pubescence. First flagellomere has some flattened setulae (better expressed in females) near the base, visible only under high magnifications (e.g.
x 40
).

Female antenna (
Fig. 2
) rather distinct, with f 1 and f 2 fused. The compound formation about 2.4 times as long and 2 times as broad as the third flagellomere. The latter and following segments cylindrical, increasing in length distally, with verticils two to three times as long as pubescence. Female fused element is covered with peg-like and flattened setulae (
Fig. 2
), this feature being similar to that reported in
T.(S.) antennata Starý
and several other species (
Starý, 1999
).

